{
  "texts": [
    "Either through deliberate deception or subterfuge, the maligned practice assumes conscious action on the part of the perpetrator.The complexities in the American context are further detailed in various academic guidelines, which include a plethora of actions under the umbrella of plagiarism [28,29].",
    "These actions range from the direct, such as copying from a source without quotations or citations, to the more nuanced, like paraphrasing or summarizing the idea of another without attribution.",
    "Even subtle acts, such as altering sentence structure while retaining its original words, or vice versa, are considered plagiarism.",
    "Additionally, the unacknowledged use of audio, video, or other media sources, submitting the work of another student as their own, or using information from an expert interview without proper attribution, are all deemed to be forms of plagiarism.",
    "Furthermore, the scope of plagiarism in American academia extends to the realms of collaboration and recycling one's work-selfplagiarism [30]."
  ]
}